For {= official_instrument =}+ official {= start_year =}-{= end_year =} instruments, supply an official source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL) showing how the instrument materially assigns, conditions, or protects against electric-grid cost responsibility for data centers, computational loads, high-density or speculative loads, co-located loads, high-impact loads, very large customers, or other large electric loads.

Treat one official instrument as the unit of work: a bill, enacted law, commission order, docketed tariff approval, tariff schedule, approved or proposed filing, FERC order or rulemaking, RTO/ISO tariff process, service agreement, official technical conference, official show-cause proceeding, or comparable authority-issued instrument. Do not split routine docket filings into separate entries unless the filing itself materially changes cost responsibility, service obligations, tariff status, or a required deadline.

For each instrument, name the authority, jurisdiction or market, and instrument identifier. Also report the instrument type, source-stated large-load scope label, status as of the source check, `source_checked_date`, latest material update date and action, official source type, affected utility or market when public, factual cost-responsibility levers, term basis, publicness or access state, and any visible stale-source or official-status conflict.

Official sources include commission docket or order pages, official order PDFs, legislature bill pages or bill text, FERC pages or eLibrary identifiers, RTO/ISO filing, tariff, or stakeholder pages, and utility tariff/process pages when the page is tied to regulator approval or a stated tariff process. Official press releases and reports can establish status, context, and identifiers; exact obligation values should come from operative text when that text is public. Do not use secondary trackers, industry compilations, news, advocacy, law-firm commentary, or general summaries as the submitted URL unless the URL is controlled by the issuing authority, tariffing utility, legislature, FERC, or RTO/ISO and directly supports the submitted instrument.

Instruments can be adopted, approved, proposed, pending, continued, failed, under-development, show-cause, technical-conference, or exploratory when the status is clear. General data-center policy, tax incentives, siting, water, environmental permitting, load forecasts, or reliability reports do not count unless the source itself materially addresses grid-cost responsibility or service obligations for the large load.

Requirements:
- The page must identify the official instrument, authority, jurisdiction or market, and instrument type closely enough to anchor the submitted instrument.
- The page must connect the source-stated large-load scope to grid-cost responsibility, cost-shift protection, interconnection cost treatment, tariff/service obligations, or comparable service conditions.
- The page must state at least one factual cost-responsibility lever or obligation basis, such as minimum bill or demand, contract term, contribution in aid of construction or upfront payment, collateral or financial assurance, termination charge, direct assignment, network-upgrade cost, generation or resource obligation, transmission-service requirement, flexibility or curtailment, reporting/transparency, customer-confidentiality/publicness, or another source-stated lever.
- The `source_checked_date` must be reported, and the page must support the procedural and publicness posture reported for the instrument as of that check: status, latest material update date or action, source type, affected utility or market when public, and whether the cited evidence is public final terms, public proposed terms, official summary only, redacted, portal-limited, stale, no-material-change, or conflicting.
- The submitted evidence text must stay within what the cited official URL supports. Excerpts or source-backed notes should explicitly cover instrument identity, the large-load cost-responsibility connection, at least one concrete lever or obligation basis, and the status/publicness posture. Do not import facts from secondary sources, companion articles, broad policy summaries, or related dockets unless the submitted official URL itself states or directly links the same facts for the instrument.
